
[1]diadem

   DIADEM, n. [Gr., to gird; to bind. L.]

   1. Anciently, a head-band or fillet worn by kings as a badge or
   royalty. It was made of silk, linen or wool, and tied round the temples
   and forehead, the ends being tied behind and let fall on the neck. It
   was usually white and plain; sometimes embroidered with gold, or set
   with pearls and precious stones.

   2. In modern usage, the mark or badge of royalty, worn on the head; a
   crown; and figuratively, empire; supreme power.

   3. A distinguished or principal ornament.

   A diadem of beauty. Isaiah 28.
